>
> Hear any pinking at all??? No?? Still could be too high compression from
> not verifying deck height during assembly. Could also be just running too
> lean. How did you adjust the mixture??? Float level too low will lean you
> out = heat. So would a vacuum leak. A weak fuel pump that can't keep up
> will likewise drop the fuel level in the carb and lean you out = heat.
>
> >Another subject: There definitely is a rpm dependant vibration in the
beast.
> >Pisses me off as I spent a lot of money having the whole thing balanced
> >before I assembled it. How long till this engine flies apart?
>
>
> A few possibles: fouled plug, cracked plug insulator, bad HT wire, cracked
> dizzy cap, valve lash closing up, cylinder studs
> cracked/stretching/pulling, piston installed 180° wrong, head seal going
> south due to unparallel machining of either the case or head or mismatched
> cylinder shims. cracked or burned valve or piston or head from
overheating.
>
> Check and proof the ignition first, then the fuel system. If that's all
> good, teardown is probably required to find the problem.
>
> Note if it ran smoothly for 200 miles then developed the vibration, it's
